Executive Summary

This report documents a complete Security Operations Center (SOC) investigation workflow, simulating adversary activity against a Windows endpoint within a controlled, isolated laboratory environment.
The investigation encompassed network reconnaissance, service enumeration, SMB discovery, authentication testing, file access analysis, and security event investigation. The simulated attack activity originated from a Kali Linux machine directed against a Windows 10 endpoint, which was monitored through host-based security logging and SIEM capabilities.
The objective of the engagement was to identify attacker behavior, collect and preserve security evidence, analyze Indicators of Compromise (IOCs), map observed activity to the MITRE ATT&CK framework, and produce actionable security recommendations.
The investigation successfully demonstrated the end-to-end process by which a SOC analyst detects and investigates suspicious network activity, unauthorized authentication attempts, and potential lateral movement technique


Objective

The objectives of this investigation were to:
Perform reconnaissance against a Windows endpoint.
Identify exposed network services.
Analyze SMB-based attack activity.
Simulate authentication attempts.
Collect Windows security evidence.
Investigate suspicious login activity.
Map attacker techniques to the MITRE ATT&CK framework.
Develop detection and remediation recommendations.




Investigation Methodology

The investigation followed a structured SOC incident response methodology, consisting of the following phases:
Reconnaissance
Service Enumeration
Authentication Analysis
Attack Simulation
Log Collection
Threat Analysis
MITRE ATT&CK Mapping
